dCYO1C03uGjlI8YVuWi7__4oWSEke\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring build conditions**\\n\\nI'm considering whether to separate the `JavaExec` from the test implementation. I realize that without coverage, I won't see the results unless the agent is inherited, which doesn't seem right. So, I’m thinking it might make sense to inspect the build scripts and the plugin for dynamic coverage, potentially covering all tests instead. I'm curious if this could streamline the process and improve overall visibility of the testing outcomes!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_lljetC3IA7J0WMmRclrbHv8M|fc_06ccf7802425f9cd0169fbdd6afff4819d997a5d999706e7c6", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "rg \"dynamic-access|natively-collected|graalvmNative\" -n build.gradle settings.gradle tests/src/ant/ant/1.6/build.gradle gradle forge | head -200"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 720, "output": 2127, "cacheRead": 25088, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 27935, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1778113867076, "responseId": "resp_06ccf7802425f9cd0169fbdd4b8c10819db1496e7479f75d41"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_lljetC3IA7J0WMmRclrbHv8M|fc_06ccf7802425f9cd0169fbdd6afff4819d997a5d999706e7c6", "toolName": "bash", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "tests/src/ant/ant/1.6/build.gradle:28:graalvmNative {\nforge/benchmarks/benchmark_runner.py:67:        \"--keep-tests-without-dynamic-access\",\nforge/benchmarks/benchmark_runner.py:70:            \"Forwarded to add_new_library_support.py. Keeps generated tests for dynamic-access strategies \"\nforge/benchmarks/benchmark_runner.py:71:            \"even when no dynamic-access coverage is added.\"\nforge/benchmarks/benchmark_runner.py:217:        cmd.append(\"--keep-tests-without-dynamic-access\")\nforge/strategies/predefined_strategies.json:62:  